<h2>Final Thoughts from Isabella Nightshade</h2>
<p>If you choose to spend a night where the past lingers, come with curiosity wrapped in respect. The best stays ask something of you: patience for a slow conversation with place, openness to how architecture frames memory, and attention to the people who steward these properties. Haunted hotels and inns offer you a kind of travel that is less about spectacle and more about intimacy—an invitation to feel the continuity between living rooms and long rooms, between living memory and the stories that travel.</p>
<p>In your planning, balance the romance of rumor with the practicalities of comfort and safety. Book mindfully, ask kindly, and permit the building its dignity. Whether you hear a piano in an empty parlor or simply sense that the wallpaper has kept secrets, you will carry the experience home as a layer added to your own history of places you have loved.</p>
